article.headline: Lady Techsters prevail despite injuries to guards
article.linkText: Louisiana Tech grit out win over W. Kentucky
article.story:
RUSTON, La. (AP) -- For a while there, Louisiana Tech head coach
Kurt Budke thought he might have to suit up.

In the first half, starting guards Tasha Crain and Shan Moore
both tumbled to the floor. Crain screamed in pain as she twisted
her left ankle going up for a layup less than five minutes into the
Lady Techsters' game against Western Kentucky.

Then with just under four minutes to go in the half, Moore
landed on her right knee, seemingly unable to play the rest of the
game, just like her fallen teammate.

But Moore returned and came back to score a career-high 20
points and Louisiana Tech (No. 20 ESPN/USA Today, No. 21 AP) powered past Western Kentucky 73-60 Thursday night.

"With what happened to us tonight, how can I be upset in any
way with this game?" Budke said. "All of the adversity that we
had there for a while, hey, I'll take this win."

The three-time defending Western Athletic Conference champion
Lady Techsters (3-1) got a 7-of-10 field goal performance and
two-of-three free throw production out of Moore, whose prior
career-best was 19 points earlier in the week against Mississippi
State.

With Crain out for nearly 14 minutes, the Techsters had to
switch regular shooting guard Lakiste Barkus to the point and she
responded with 17 points, five steals and three assists.

"I knew I had to step up my game, both offensively and
defensively," Barkus said. "I had to look at myself closer and
figure out how I could help my team."

Crystal Kelly led Western Kentucky (2-3) with 29 points and 13
rebounds. Cacie Pope had 10 points for the Lady Hilltoppers.

Tech shot 51.9 percent from the field, including 59.1 in the
final half. Both teams ended with 35 rebounds.
